I went back to Reed several times since 1968.  The last time<br>
time I was there was to drive around the grounds with my wife of 25 years<br>
and my then-17 year old son.  What used to be, that is, in the period of<br>
1965 to 1968, a robust and bustling factory of the limbless, <br>
the faceless (literally) and the numb, was then a quiet almost university<br>
type campus.  I felt such a void.  The clatter of the refuse<br>
end of the war was a mere garden of recall, a quiet <br>
rest home of the remembrance of the Oddments and Endments<br>
of so many lives.
